data.content:
## What breaks: sync API removal for the Cosmos DB provider

Starting with EF Core 9 (.NET 9), the Cosmos provider began **rejecting synchronous operations by default**, throwing `InvalidOperationException`. In .NET 10, your code only worked because you opted in with something like:

```csharp
options.UseCosmos(...).ConfigureWarnings(w =>
    w.Ignore(CosmosEventId.SyncNotSupported));
```

**In .NET 11, this opt-in is removed entirely.** The sync-over-async bridge is gone — all four of your methods (`ToList()`, `First()`, `Count()`, `SaveChanges()`) will throw `InvalidOperationException` at runtime regardless of configuration.

## The fix: convert to async

```csharp
public class ProductRepository
{
    private readonly CosmosDbContext _context;

    public async Task<List<Product>> GetAllAsync()
    {
        return await _context.Products.ToListAsync();
    }

    public async Task<Product> GetByIdAsync(int id)
    {
        return await _context.Products.FirstAsync(p => p.Id == id);
    }

    public async Task<int> GetCountAsync()
    {
        return await _context.Products.CountAsync();
    }

    public async Task SaveAsync(Product product)
    {
        _context.Products.Add(product);
        await _context.SaveChangesAsync();
    }
}
```

**Key changes:**
- `ToList()` → `ToListAsync()` + `await`
- `First()` → `FirstAsync()` + `await`
- `Count()` → `CountAsync()` + `await`
- `SaveChanges()` → `SaveChangesAsync()` + `await`
- All return types wrapped in `Task<T>`

The async methods come from `Microsoft.EntityFrameworkCore` (namespace already imported if you're using EF). Callers must also be updated to `await` these methods, which propagates `async` up your call chain (controllers, services, etc.).
